^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, lets do the bidding first. What should Eddy bid over 1S overcall? There are a number of choices depending on style. If you play 2D which shows a limit raise, only promises 3 trump, you can bid that. I personally like it to show 4 trumps, but many play it only promises three. There is an interesting convention known as a "|CP|8|at|Mixed Raise|CP||AT|" that some experts play to take care of this problem. |
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|They play that both a cue bid (in this case 2D) and 2N show spade raises and limit raise points. The lower of those two bids shows three card support, the higher shows four card support. So, on this auction, if you played that convention, 2D by Eddy would show three card support, 2N would show four card support. On another auction, say 1S-2D, 2N would show three card support and 3D would show four card support. |
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, since most people don't play that what are the choices. 4S is certainly a reasonable choice. The only problem is that it misdescribes the hand a bit. It is unlikely that slam is there so that is not a huge problem. Another choice is 2C, assuming you play that forcing. Some people play new suits by responder to overcaller is not forcing. However, I strongly believe that they should be forcing, just the same as new suits by responder to opener. Playing with my pards, I would bid 2C, and then 4S to show my hand.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play. Knocking out the Ace of clubs right away was a good idea. What Yvon has to worry about is his four low diamonds. One can go on hearts, and one might be able to go on clubs although that requires a 3-3 break. So, I would start the same way as Yvon, but then play it slightly differently. |
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I would ruff the diamond, play another club, ruff a diamond as he did. Then I would play K A Q of hearts pitching a diamond and then play a spade. The only real difference would be use the heart to pitch the last diamond rather than a club.|
