^-{An Introduction to New Minor Forcing}
^-|CP||at|^B@2^Z@3^*BNew Minor Forcing ^*N|cp||at|(NMF) is a convention used to discover a major suit fit when opener rebids 1NT or 2NT after opening one of a minor and receiving a response of one of a major, such as 1D-P-1H-P; 1NT-P-?. It has the following features which I will explain later.|
PG| ***** 122 ***** |


FP|2|at|

· It is a bid by responder.|
PG| ***** 123 ***** |


va|3|AT|
· It is artificial and has nothing to do with the holding in that suit.|
PG| ***** 124 ***** |


va|3|AT|
· Responder (when bidding NMF) has five or more cards in the bid major. |
PG| ***** 125 ***** |


va|3|fp||AT|
      Always true after a 1N rebid, but not always true over a 2N rebid.
      The exceptions are 1C:1H:2N:3D and 1D:1H:2N:3C.|
PG| ***** 126 ***** |


va|3|fp|2|AT|
· Responder may have four cards of the other major.|
PG| ***** 127 ***** |


va|3|AT|
· Responder must have a hand with invitational or game values.|
PG| ***** 128 ***** |


va|3|AT| 
· It is forcing for one round.|
PG| ***** 129 ***** |


va|3|AT|
· The responder may be a passed hand.|
PG| ***** 130 ***** |


va|3|AT|
· Usually the unbid minor is the NMF.|
PG| ***** 131 ***** |


va|3|AT|
· There is no NMF when opponents interfere.|
PG| ***** 132 ***** |


va|3|AT|
· It is alertable.|
PG| ***** 133 ***** |


fp||AT|


