^-
{The Third Man High - The Principles}
^-|HT|f|cs||at|^B@2^Y@3When you play as Third Hand--which is to say, when you play the third card on Partner's lead  you should generally play your highest card.|
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


AT|

When your highest cards of your Partner's led suit are in sequence, play the lowest of the sequence--not the highest.|
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


AT|

The third hand can never have a card just below the one he played. For example, if the third hand plays the Queen, hecannot have the Jack.|
PG| ***** 138 ***** |


AT|

Further, when playing third hand high and holding say @HQJ96 sequence and one of dummy's card is @H10, filling your broken sequence holding, you should play the nine and not the Jack. Or if you hold @H1097 sequence and dummy has @H8 you should play @H7--assuming dummy plays low.  |
PG| ***** 139 ***** |


AT|

When dummy has one honor card and third hand has a ^*Ihigher^*N honor card, third hand normally saves his honor unless the honor is played by dummy. However, third hand must have a card as high as the nine to insert if the honor is not played from dummy.  Lacking a nine or higher to play, third hand plays the high honor. For example, if dummy has the Queen, and you hold @SK10 or @SK9, do not play the @SK; play the @S10 or @9.|
PG| ***** 140 ***** |


AT|

When dummy has an honor that is higher than third hand's honor but played low, third hand should play as if there were no honor in dummy at all. For example, partner leads low and dummy has @DK76 and third man has @DQ45 and dummy plays low. Third hand should play the diamond Queen. |
